'''Lawrence Shankland''' (born 10 August 1995) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]. He is set to join fellow Scottish Premiership side [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on 15 June 2026.<ref name=":0" />

Shankland began his career at [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] before moving to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in 2013. He played on loan with [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]], [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] and [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] before joining [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] in 2017. He signed for [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] in 2019 and made his debut for Scotland later that year. In 2021 Shankland moved to Belgian club [[K Beerschot VA|Beerschot]], but returned to Scotland after one year, signing with Hearts.

==Club career==
===Queen's Park===
Shankland was born in [[Glasgow]] and attended [[Bannerman High School]] in [[Baillieston]].<ref name=afc15>{{cite web |url=https://www.afc.co.uk/2015/02/11/lawrence-shankland-interview-2/ |title=Lawrence Shankland interview |publisher=Aberdeen FC  |date=11 February 2015 |access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> He progressed through the [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] youth system and was their top goalscorer in the [[2012–13 Scottish Third Division|2012–13 season]], having moved to the senior squad straight from the under-17 team;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/shankland-given-opportunity-at-aberdeen/ |title=Shankland given opportunity at Aberdeen |work=www.spfl.co.uk |publisher=Scottish Professional Football League |date=25 June 2013 |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref> he also worked part-time as a tool setter in a local plumbing supplies company, a position arranged by the amateur club to help their young players earn a wage.<ref name=afc15/> He scored his first senior goal on 4 August 2012, aged 16, in a [[Scottish League Cup]] tie against [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrieonians]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roache |first1=Ian |title=Sean Burns looks back to when 16-year-old Lawrence Shankland announced his arrival as goalscorer |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/sport/football/dundee-united/990043/sean-burns-looks-back-to-when-16-year-old-lawrence-shankland-announced-his-arrival-as-goalscorer/ |access-date=16 July 2020 |work=The Courier |date=2 October 2019 |location=Dundee}}</ref>

Shankland signed for [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] at the end of the season.<ref name = "queen's park"/><ref name = "under20">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23030004 |title=Aberdeen sign former Rangers winger Gregg Wylde |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=24 June 2013 |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref> He was one of three Queen's Park players to move to top flight Scottish clubs at that time, as [[Andrew Robertson (footballer)|Andy Robertson]] and [[Aidan Connolly]] signed for [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref name = "queen's park">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23199925 |title=Young Queen's Park trio make rare jump to SPL from Third Division |first=Kenny |last=Crawford |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=5 July 2013 |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=afc15/> [[Blair Spittal]] also made the move to Dundee United a year later.

===Aberdeen===
Shankland was initially placed in the Aberdeen [[Aberdeen F.C. Reserves and Academy|under-20 squad]], as he adjusted to full-time professional training.<ref name = "under20"/><ref name=afc15/> He made his debut appearance for Aberdeen in September 2014, in a 3–2 victory against [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/mobile/matches/5115.php#.VEIIJRawS5Y |title=FT: Aberdeen 3 Inverness CT 2 |publisher=Aberdeen FC |work=www.afc.co.uk |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref> After impressing in the under-20s, scoring plenty of goals, and making first team appearances as a substitute, Shankland signed a new contract to run until summer 2017;<ref>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen: Adam Rooney & Niall McGinn sign new deals|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30582242|publisher=BBC |work=BBC Sport|date=22 December 2014 |access-date=22 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=afc15/> however, he was loaned to lower-division clubs for the vast majority of its duration. At the end of the [[2016–17 Aberdeen F.C. season|2016–17 season]], Aberdeen confirmed that Shankland would be leaving the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40113519|title=Aberdeen: Ash Taylor & Lawrence Shankland join players leaving Pittodrie|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=31 May 2017|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref>

====Dunfermline loan====
Shankland moved to [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] on loan for the latter part of the [[2013–14 Scottish League One|2013–14 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25650100 |title=Aberdeen's Lawrence Shankland joins Dunfermline on loan |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=8 January 2014 |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref> The 18-year-old striker scored seven league goals during his short spell in Fife; however, injury prevented him taking part in the ''Pars''' end-of-season [[2013–14 Scottish Championship#Championship play-offs|promotion play-off]] with [[Fife derby|local rivals]] [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]] which ended in defeat.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cowdenbeath-mad.co.uk/news/tmnw/cowdenbeath_v_dunfermline_at_central_park_match_preview_832903/index.shtml |title=Cowdenbeath V Dunfermline at Central Park – Match Preview |work=CowdenbeathMad |publisher=FootyMad |date=13 May 2014 |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref>

====St Mirren and Morton loans====
Shankland was loaned to [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] in August 2015 for the rest of the 2015–16 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Loan Signing: Lawrence Shankland|url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=46391|publisher=St Mirren F.C.|work=www.saintmirren.net|date=26 August 2015|access-date=26 August 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924094054/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=46391|archive-date=24 September 2015}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the ''Buddies'' in a 2–1 home defeat to [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] on 18 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=St Mirren 1–2 Raith Rovers match report|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34217202|publisher=BBC |work=BBC Sport|date=18 September 2015 |access-date=20 September 2015}}</ref> Shankland scored 10 goals in 32 appearances during his loan spell, and returned to Aberdeen at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=55088|title=Squad Update|publisher=St Mirren Official website|access-date=3 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605114158/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=55088|archive-date=5 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In July 2016 it was confirmed that Shankland had returned to St Mirren, on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=56577 |title=Loan Signing: Lawrence Shankland |publisher=St Mirren FC |date=19 July 2016 |access-date=19 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825214145/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=56577 |archive-date=25 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, having failed to score any league goals in the first half of the season, his St Mirren deal was cut short and on 11 January 2017, he moved on loan to their [[Renfrewshire derby|rivals]], fellow [[Scottish Championship]] side [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gmfc.net/2017/01/11/aberdeen-striker-lawrence-shankland-joins-on-loan/ |title=Aberdeen striker Lawrence Shankland joins on loan |first=Jonathan |last=Mitchell |publisher=Greenock Morton FC |date=11 January 2017 |access-date=11 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113091010/http://gmfc.net/2017/01/11/aberdeen-striker-lawrence-shankland-joins-on-loan/ |archive-date=13 January 2017 }}</ref> After helping the club to a fourth-place finish, his final appearance for Morton was in the [[2016–17 Scottish Premiership#Premiership play-offs|Scottish Premiership playoff]] defeat to Dundee United.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39833721 |title=Dundee United 3–0 Greenock Morton|work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=12 May 2017 |access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref>

===Ayr United===
In September 2017, free agent Shankland signed a short-term contract to play for [[Scottish League One]] club [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] until the following January.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/ayr-united-sign-former-aberdeen-11133101 |title=Ayr United sign former Aberdeen striker Lawrence Shankland as Ian McCall bids to boost side's League One title bid|work=Daily Record |date=8 September 2017 |access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref> On 24 March 2018 he scored a hat-trick against former club Queen's Park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43528434|title=Scottish League One: Ayr strengthen grip on top spot, Forfar boost hopes|work=BBC Sport|date=24 March 2018|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Ayr won [[2017–18 Scottish League One|the league]] by one point, and after finishing with 29 goals, Shankland was named as the division's [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year]].<ref name=pfa18>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43944186 |title=Scott Brown: Celtic captain voted PFA Scotland player of the year 2017/18 |work=BBC Sport |date=29 April 2018 |access-date=10 May 2018}}</ref>

He started the 2018–19 season with a hat-trick against former club Morton in the [[2018–19 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AyrUnitedFC/status/1018155948362358784|title=GOOOAAAALLLL! &#124; HAT-TRICK @Shankland_25. A cool chip over Ryan Scully.pic.twitter.com/RU3oPLS07a|first=Ayr|last=United|date=14 July 2018}}</ref> On 28 July, he scored a "stunning goal" from 45 yards as Ayr defeated [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] to qualify for the knockout stage of the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44994431 |title=League Cup: Partick Thistle 0-2 Ayr United, Morton 5-0 Albion Rovers |work=BBC Sport |date=28 July 2018 |access-date=28 July 2018}}</ref> With a goal against Dunfermline on 25 August 2018, Shankland moved to 41 goals in 42 games for the ''Honest Men''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45230784 |title=Ayr United 4-1 Dunfermline Athletic |work=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2018|access-date=27 August 2018}}</ref>

In November 2018, he scored four goals in a [[2018–19 Scottish Championship|league fixture]] away to Dundee United which ended 5–0 and put Ayr five points clear at the top of the table.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46312740 |title= Dundee United 0-5 Ayr United |work=BBC Sport |date=30 November 2018|access-date=1 December 2018}}</ref> However he then sustained an injury, and Ayr's form deteriorated in his absence. He returned towards the end of the season, but the team's campaign ended with defeat to Inverness CT in the opening round of the [[2018–19 Scottish Premiership#Premiership play-offs|Premiership promotion play-offs]], having finished in fourth position.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inverness CT 1-1 Ayr United (4-2 agg): hosts set up play-off semi-final meeting with Dundee United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48165445|work=BBC Sport |date=11 May 2019|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> Shankland, whose total return was 34 goals in 41 games, was nominated for the division's PFA Player of the Year Award,<ref>{{cite web|title=Player of the Year: Old Firm quartet vie for PFA Scotland top prize|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/48124177|work=BBC Sport |date=5 May 2019|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> but lost out to another prolific striker, [[Stephen Dobbie]]. Both were named in the [[PFA Scotland Team of the Year#2018–19|Team of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/sport/1741717/kilmarnocks-steve-clarke-and-celtics-james-forrest-win-pfa-manager-and-player-of-the-year-awards/ | title=Kilmarnock's Steve Clarke and Celtic's James Forrest win PFA manager and player of the year awards | publisher=[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|Press and Journal]] | date=5 May 2019 | access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref>

===Dundee United===
On 3 July 2019 it was announced that Shankland had left Ayr to join fellow Championship side Dundee United on a three-year contract, turning down offers from other clubs in both England and Scotland.<ref>{{cite web |title=United Announce Shankland Signing |url=https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/6126/UNITED-ANNOUNCE-SHANKLAND-SIGNING.html?key=dufc |website=Dundee United Football Club |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref><ref name="BBCsport03072019">{{cite news |title=Dundee Utd confirm Lawrence Shankland signing as striker leaves Ayr Utd |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48862322 |access-date=3 July 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=3 July 2019}}</ref> He scored on his debut for the club in a [[Scottish League Cup]] tie against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] on 12 July 2019,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48925615 |title=Hearts 1–1 Dundee United  |work=BBC |access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref> and scored four goals in a 4–1 victory against [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] on the opening day of the [[2019–20 Scottish Championship]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dundee United 4–1 Inverness Caledonian Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49136071|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Lewis|first=Jane|date=3 August 2019|access-date=3 August 2019}}</ref> Shankland was named [[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners#2019–20 season|Scottish Championship Player of the Month]] for August 2019, having scored eight goals in four appearances during the month.<ref name=august19>{{cite web|title=Awards Double For Dundee United|url=https://spfl.co.uk/news/awards-double-for-dundee-united|publisher=Scottish Professional Football League|date=10 September 2019|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> The season was suspended in March 2020 due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland]], and curtailed a month later, with Dundee United declared winners and promoted;<ref name=ends20>{{cite news| url= https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11781/11973775/scottish-championship-league-one-and-league-two-seasons-end-after-dundee-vote-for-spfl-resolution| title=Scottish Championship, League One and League Two seasons end after Dundee vote for SPFL resolution| website=[[BBC Sport]]| date=16 April 2020| access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref> up to that point Shankland had scored 24 league goals to finish as the division's top scorer, and maintained the  ratio of almost a goal-per-game he had set at Ayr, with a total of 28 from 33 appearances.

On 12 January 2021, Shankland scored with a "wonder strike" from {{convert|53|yards|m}} to secure a 2–2 draw against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Goal of the season? Watch Shankland's 53-yard wonder strike |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/av/football/55641336 |access-date=17 January 2021 |work=BBC Sport |date=12 January 2021}}</ref>

===Beerschot===

On 11 August 2021, Shankland moved to Belgian side [[K Beerschot VA|Beerschot]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beerschot.be/en/news/dundee-united-striker-lawrence-shankland-signs-beerschot|title=DUNDEE UNITED STRIKER LAWRENCE SHANKLAND SIGNS FOR BEERSCHOT|publisher=K Beerschot VA|date=11 August 2021|access-date=11 August 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/6953/LAWRENCE-SHANKLAND-DEPARTS-FOR-BEERSCHOT.html|title=LAWRENCE SHANKLAND DEPARTS FOR BEERSCHOT|publisher=Dundee United FC|date=11 August 2021|access-date=11 August 2021}}</ref> Shankland scored five league goals for Beerschot during the 2021–22 season as they were relegated from the Belgian top division.<ref name = hearts/>

===Heart of Midlothian===

==== 2022–23 ====
Shankland returned to Scottish football in July 2022, signing a three-year contract with [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]].<ref name="hearts">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62242130 |title=Lawrence Shankland: Scotland striker joins Hearts from Beerschot |website=BBC Sport |date=20 July 2022 |accessdate=20 July 2022}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Hearts in a 1–1 draw with [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] at [[Easter Road]] on 7 August 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hibernian 1-1 Hearts: Martin Boyle marks Easter Road return with late Edinburgh derby equaliser |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/36621/12665263/hibernian-1-1-hearts-martin-boyle-marks-easter-road-return-with-late-edinburgh-derby-equaliser |access-date=2023-01-27 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref>

After a season-ending injury to club captain [[Craig Gordon]] in a match on 28 December 2022, Shankland was named team captain for the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Meikle |first=Blair |date=2022-12-29 |title=Lawrence Shankland Hearts captain for season as Robbie Neilson explains decision |url=https://www.footballscotland.co.uk/spfl/scottish-premiership/lawrence-shankland-captain-hearts-season-25853555 |access-date=2024-07-09 |website=Football Scotland |language=en}}</ref>

Shankland became the first Hearts' player since [[John Robertson (footballer, born 1964)|John Robertson]] in the [[1991–92 in Scottish football|1991–92 season]] to score 20 goals in all competitions following his goal in the [[2022–23 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]] against Hibs to make it 2–0.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Galindo |first=Alan |date=2023-01-23 |title=Hearts star Lawrence Shankland tipped for 30 goals after breaking 20-goal mark |url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/sport/hearts-star-lawrence-shankland-tipped-26047523 |access-date=2023-01-27 |website=EdinburghLive |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2023–24 ====
In Gordon's continued absence, Shankland retained team captaincy for the [[2023–24 Heart of Midlothian F.C. season|2023–24 season]]. His second season at Hearts showed a similar prolific form as his first, hitting 50 club goals by February 2024, less than 18 months after joining the club, becoming only the second player to hit the milestone in the 21st century alongside [[Jamie Walker (footballer)|Jamie Walker]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-02-09 |title=Lawrence Shankland backs himself to keep scoring after hitting 50th Hearts goal |url=https://www.thenational.scot/sport/24108275.shankland-backs-keep-scoring-50-hearts-goals/ |access-date=2024-07-09 |website=The National |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2024–2026 ====
During the [[2024–25 Heart of Midlothian F.C. season|2024–25 season]], Shankland's goalscoring output in the early part of the campaign was lower than in the previous season, with analysis noting a reduced conversion rate despite a similar volume of chances.<ref>{{cite web |last=Petrie |first=Andrew |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/cy5lk57l1p9o |title=What's gone wrong for misfiring Shankland? |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 October 2024 }}</ref> In July 2025, Shankland signed a new three-year contract with the club.<ref name="auto1">{{cite web |url=https://www.heartsfc.co.uk/blogs/news/shankland-signs-new-deal |title=Shankland signs new deal |publisher=Heart of Midlothian F.C. |date=3 July 2025 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McLauchlin |first=Brian |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cq53wq1nzn5o |title=Shankland reveals Jock the Jambo role in new Hearts contract |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 July 2025 }}</ref>

In the [[2025–26 Heart of Midlothian F.C. season|2025–26 season]], he continued as club captain and contributed key goals in the title challenge, including in a 3–1 victory over [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] on 26 October 2025 that increased Hearts' lead at the top of the table.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report/_/gameId/742387 |title=Hearts beat injury-hit Celtic, go eight points clear in SPFL |publisher=ESPN |date=26 October 2025 }}</ref> He later netted the winning goal in a 2–1 victory against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on 4 May 2026.<ref>{{cite web |last=Murray |first=Ewan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/may/04/hearts-rangers-scottish-premiership-match-report |title=Title-chasing Hearts clear crucial hurdle as Shankland shatters Rangers' hopes |publisher=The Guardian |date=4 May 2026 }}</ref> Later that month, on 16 May, Shankland opened the scoring in a crucial away match against Celtic on the final matchday of the season, but the team fell to a 3–1 defeat, finishing second in the title race.<ref>{{cite web |last=Binnie |first=Adam |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11781/13544422/celtic-win-scottish-premiership-title-but-does-hearts-emergence-mean-the-scottish-football-landscape-has-changed-forever |title=Celtic win Scottish Premiership title but does Hearts' emergence mean the Scottish football landscape has changed forever? |publisher=Sky Sports |date=16 May 2026 }}</ref> He ended the season with 16 league goals, just one short of top scorer [[Tawanda Maswanhise]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/celtic-surge-late-as-hearts-surrender-top-spot-42875419 |title=Celtic surge late as Hearts surrender top spot |publisher=OneFootball |date=16 May 2026 }}</ref>

===Rangers===
On 26 May 2026, Rangers announced Shankland on a two-year deal with an option for an additional year. He will join [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] once the summer transfer window opens on 15 June 2026.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=https://www.rangers.co.uk/article/rangers-announce-signing-of-lawrence-shankland/3COV8MiuUZ9gqCl3Xt67xu |title=Rangers Announce Signing of Lawrence Shankland |publisher=Rangers |date=26 May 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
Shankland represented [[Scotland national under-18 football team|Scotland under-18s]] in [[Victory Shield]] matches against the other home nations in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/ssfa/scottish_football.cfm?page=3383 |title=Scotland Under 18s 2012 Photo Gallery |work=Scottish FA |publisher=The Scottish Schools' Football Association 2014 |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref> He was first selected for the [[Scotland national under-21 football team]] in March 2015; he made his debut away to [[Hungary national under-21 football team|Hungary]], scoring two late goals in a 2–1 victory. He made three other under-21 appearances, also in 2015, producing one draw and two defeats.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=113593 |title=Lawrence Shankland |work=www.scottishfa.co.uk |publisher=Scottish Football Association |access-date=22 September 2018}}</ref>

On 1 October 2019, [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] manager [[Steve Clarke]] called up Shankland to the senior squad for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49893529 |title=Lawrence Shankland: Scotland call-up for Dundee United striker |date=1 October 2019 |website=BBC Sport|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> He won his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] when he came on as a second-half substitute in the side's 4–0 defeat by [[Russia national football team|Russia]] on 10 October<ref name="ScotRussia">{{cite news |last1=Forsyth |first1=Roddy |title=Sorry Scotland thrashed by Russia to leave Nations League as their only Euro 2020 hope |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/10/10/scotland-thrashed-russia-leave-nations-league-euro-2020-hope/ |access-date=10 October 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=10 October 2019}}</ref> (playing alongside national team captain [[Andy Robertson]] for the first time since their time at Queen's Park in the fourth tier of Scottish football, nearly seven years earlier)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/17939061.queens-park-share-nostalgic-snap-robertson-shankland-teammates-scotland-call-up|title=Queen's Park share nostalgic snap of Robertson and Shankland as teammates after Scotland call-up|publisher=Glasgow Times |date=1 October 2019|access-date=10 September 2021}}</ref> and three days later made his first start and scored his first goal, the fourth in a 6–0 victory over [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] at [[Hampden Park]].<ref name="BBCScotSanMar">{{cite news |last1=Lamont |first1=Alasdair |title=Scotland 6–0 San Marino |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49949350 |access-date=13 October 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=13 October 2019}}</ref>

Shankland was recalled to the squad in March 2023, as an injury replacement for [[Ché Adams]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65080102 |title=Scotland call up for Lawrence Shankland as Che Adams & Anthony Ralston drop out |website=BBC Sport |date=26 March 2023 |accessdate=26 March 2023}}</ref> He scored his second international goal on 16 November 2023, a late equaliser in a [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] match against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]].<ref name = Georgia>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67444687 |title=Georgia 2-2 Scotland: Should Lawrence Shankland be on the plane to Germany next summer? |first=Nick |last=McPheat |website=BBC Sport |date=16 November 2023 |accessdate=17 November 2023}}</ref> Shankland had again been a late addition to the squad as an injury replacement for Adams.<ref name = Georgia/>

On 23 March 2024, Shankland was named in Scotland's starting XI for the first time since 2019 in a [[UEFA Euro 2024]] warm-up match against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/24205834.netherlands-4-scotland-0-instant-reaction-burning-issues/|title= Netherlands 4 Scotland 0: Steve Clarke's men suffer mauling in Euro 2024 warm-up game|website=Herald Scotland|date=23 March 2024|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, he was named in Scotland's 26-man squad for Euro 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> He played the final eight minutes of the 5–1 loss to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in the opening match of the tournament on 14 June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> He went on to appear as a substitute against both [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1-1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref>

After a year out of the international team, Shankland was recalled for Scotland's [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in November 2025.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/cn51g1yxl0wo |title=Shankland eyes World Cup after Scotland recall |website=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2025 |accessdate=21 November 2025}}</ref> He scored the second goal in a famous 4&ndash;2 win against Denmark on 18 November, allowing Scotland to top their group and qualify automatically for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]]; their first appearance at the tournament since [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Murray |first=Ewan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/nov/18/scotland-denmark-world-cup-2026-qualifying-match-report |title=Tierney and McLean send Scotland to World Cup with thrilling win against Denmark |work=The Guardian |date=18 November 2025 }}</ref>

